INNER TURF FOR THREE YEAR OLDS AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE STARTED FOR A CLAIMING PRICE OF $5,000 OR LESS IN 2022 - 2023 OR CLAIMING PRICE $10,000. Three Year Olds, 122 lbs.; Older, 126 lbs. Non-winners Of Two Races Since April 15 Allowed 2 lbs. A Race Since Th en Allowed 4 lbs. Claiming Price $10,000 (Races Where Entered For $4,000 Or Less Not Considered For Allowances).
RACE.FOOTNOTES: LION KINGDOM was allowed to settle trailing the pack in the early stages of the race, continued to see the field in upper stretch, quickly burst between rivals two deep at the eighth pole and was full of run late getting up in time just a few jumps before the wire. ROCKET JOE COPPER rated kindly while well in hand on the fence at the half behind the leaders, waited on the rail throughout the final turn waiting for a seam, took command in the four path at the sixteenth pole and was caught nearing the wire by the fast closing winner in the end. MAYITO stalked near the back two wide at the half, was asked for more run with three furlongs to go, angled out widest in the seven path entering the stretch and was gaining to the wire getting up in time to win the nod for third in a three horse photo. BLUE MAX had a good spot just outside tracking the top duo down the backstretch, battled between for the front in the two path at the top of the lane and fought on willingly to the wire holding for a minor share. MASTER SPY threw his head as the gate opened , travelled four wide into the first turn, settled in mid pack four deep down the backside, bid four wide with three eighths remaining, poked his head in front brief turning for home and gave way between foes in deep stretch. STOP THE HUMBUG settled on the rail near the back at the half mile pole, was on hold inside behind horses through the far turn, was pushed out to the six path for the stretch drive and was not involved late while finishing up evenly with an eighth left to run. HIATUS was reined back on the rail through the first turn to track the early frontrunner down the back straight, could not keep position with others midpoint on the far turn and was not a factor running in the stretch. BIG INVESTMENT took the field into the first turn clearing to the rail by the time the field entered the backstretch, set the fractions into the final turn, was collared by multiple rivals at the quarter pole outside and stopped on the fence at the furlong marker.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: MASSETO (GB) had a very good inside position watching the top three contest for the front in this compact field with three furlongs from home, was nestled behind the front threesome waiting in hand throughout the turn, shifted out two wide for the stretch drive, quickly took control at the eighth pole and was going away when crossing the finish line. NAPA SPIRIT (IRE) was away slowly, brushed inside at the start, offered an early move three wide to engage with the leaders three furlongs from home, was still in the mix at the top of the lane and tired between foes in the four path at the sixteenth pole.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: CLASSY WHISPER had a good spot behind the pacesetter at the half, was under a snug hold waiting inside on the final turn, slipped up the fence turning for home, shifted just outside two deep at the furlong marker, burst between horses at the sixteenth pole and was edging away nearing the wire. UNDER SURVEILLANCE sat just outside tracking the top pair down the back straight, was in range of the front runners with two furlongs left to go, battled between foes turning for home and determinedly fought on to capture the place award. QUIET SUNDAY broke slowly at the start, was unhurried for the most part of the race trailing until the stretch run, angled widest in the nine path to start his rally in upper stretch and closed belatedly outside to be a non threatening third in the end. BLAST IN THE SNOW tracked the early frontrunner down the backside, confronted the leader with three eighths to the wire, assumed command with three sixteenths from home, was headed outside in mid stretch and gave way to the line. MIDWAY MISCHIEF was fanned six wide entering the first turn, was asked to keep up with others midpoint on the far turn, had a chance for a share of the prize six deep in upper stretch but was one paced late to the finish. MIDNIGHT ARKLE was squeezed at the break, stalked near the back at the half inside, waited in the third flight on the rail when the field bunched up through the far turn, finally found a seam at the furlong marker and when clear finished up willingly to the wire. NONNO'S LITTLE BOY stalked near the rear three wide at the half mile marker, offered an early move five wide around runners with three furlongs left to run, loomed a threat six wide at the top of the lane and stalled in the final furlong. BE LIKE CLINT settled close to the back in the beginning, put in a brief turn of foot with runners on either side through the far turn and showed little driving to the wire. ZAKHARI travelled in the middle of the pack three wide down the backside, was shuffled between runners at the three furlong marker losing a few positions on the far turn, lost his lane in the eight path between horses at the furlong marker and could not make any impression running to the finish in the late stages of the race. SHAMATEUR settled in the middle of the pack inside in the beginning, advanced through the backside to take closer order to the leaders into the far turn, was in tight between runners at the quarter pole, had no path in upper stretch and could not factor running to the finish. WAVE BABY travelled four wide in midfield in the early stages of the race, was ridden for more at the three furlong marker to be in the mix for a small share at the top of the lane and retreated between foes in the final eighth. SMART SKY took the field into the first turn, continued to dictate the pace down the back straight, was collared outside with three eighths remaining and backed away through the field in mid stretch.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: A GAL FOR T J took command from the onset, set the fractions at the half, was let out a notch when mildly challenged on the far turn, opened up on her rivals at the top of the stretch and comfortably came home for the victory in the end. HALLANVAARA stalked near the rear in the beginning stages of the race, rallied splitting foes in the five path entering the stretch and found more in the last eighth to close well to capture the place share late. ALBERTA BE MINE was keen early running under the wire for the first time, settled in midfield inside down the backstretch, followed the winner saving ground throughout the final turn and was outfinished in the final sixteenth for second money. ZIPPITY DAY travelled in midfield four deep at the half mile marker, was ridden three wide midway on the far turn to no avail, was shuffled back some six wide at the top of the lane and grinded to the wire under left handed urging to finish late with energy to get a minor role in the end. REINS OF PURPLE stalked on the rail near the back of the pack, started to gain on rivals on the fence running through the far turn, angled outside in upper stretch, shifted back towards the rail in the final furlong but could not make any headway in deep stretch. GOLD FORESTER was in hand on the rail watching the loose leader in the early stages, put in a mild bid three furlongs from home, chased the winner straightening out for the drive and gave way in deep stretch losing positions late. JOLENE JOLENE tracked the leader three wide down the backside, was asked to go after the pacesetter on the far turn three eighths from home, made no gain and tired between foes at the furlong marker. TENPENNY NAIL reared at the break to trail the field considerably down the backstretch and could not overcome the poor start to be involved in the stretch run.
